title: For Sale:  SAFETY ALERT TO ALL SMITH &WESSON M &P SHIELD OWNER OUT THERE
postcontent:
SAFETY ALERT TO ALL SMITH &WESSON M &P SHIELD OWNER OUT THERE

http://www.guns.com/2013/08/22/breaking-safety-alert-for-all-smith-wesson-shield-pistols-video/

BREAKING: Safety alert for all Smith & Wesson Shield pistols…

Reports of distributors and dealers being told to halt sales of Smith & Wesson M&P Shield pistols are flying all over the Internet, leading many to believe a recall is pending.

Fortunately, it appears the problem could be limited. Smith & Wesson has posted a “safety alert” regarding a specific malfunction of the concealed-carry pistols’ triggers.

That being said, the flaw could affect any M&P Shield manufactured prior to Aug. 19, 2013, so it may be present on essentially every Shield ever made currently on the market.

“We believe this condition is largely limited to recently manufactured M&P Shield pistols. However, out of an abundance of caution, we are asking all consumers of all M&P Shields manufactured before Aug. 19, 2013 to immediately inspect their pistols for this condition.”

What’s happening is that in some cases, the pistols’ passive trigger safety is failing to engage even if there is nothing putting pressure on the trigger. Normally the safety would prevent the trigger from getting pulled except when it’s being handled.

In addition, pistols with a stuck trigger safety are not drop-safe.

“Smith & Wesson has identified a condition where the trigger bar pin could damage the lower trigger in certain M&P Shields in a way that may affect the functionality of the drop safety feature of the firearm, potentially allowing the pistol to discharge if it is dropped” explains the Smith & Wesson safety alert.

“Any unintended discharge of a firearm has the potential to cause injury, and we ask that you STOP USING YOUR PISTOL IMMEDIATELY UNTIL IT HAS BEEN INSPECTED AND, IF THE CONDITION IS FOUND, REPAIRED.”

If you have a Shield with this problem, you’re advised to send it back to Smith & Wesson for service. If you’re uncomfortable with performing the inspection procedure Smith & Wesson is asking that you take your Shield pistol to a local M&P certified armorer for inspection.

While the pistol does have a manual safety, the passive trigger safety has a long track record for reliability and safety, and is faster and easier to use in a stressful situation. Because of this, many people opt not to use it. For those people, the Shield effectively has no safety to speak of.

Of course, if you do have this issue with your M&P Shield, Smith & Wesson will repair it for you at no cost including shipping. They are expecting a five- to seven-day turnaround on all service.
mampp shield recall

Click to enlarge.

The M&P Shield has been one of Smith & Wesson’s biggest sellers ever since they announced it. A slim, comfortable pistol designed for concealed-carry and backup use, the Shield has quickly risen to the top in terms of popularity, in part because they also have a great reputation for reliability.

Smith & Wesson has not explained what the root cause in the flaw is, it could be a missing spring or just improper fitment of the hinged trigger or trigger pin.

While this flaw does not affect their reliability in any way, it’s definitely a good idea to check your Shield’s trigger for your own safety and the safety of others.

title: For Sale:  454 Casull Ammo - 360 gr. L.B.T. - L.W.N. (1,425 fps/M.E. 1,623 ft. lbs.) - 50 Round Box (Big Game up to 2000 lbs.)
postcontent:
http://extreme-impact-ammo.com/index.php?l=product_detail&p=61

The .454 Casull is one cartridge that Buffalo Bore Ammunition does not load to it's full pressure limit. When loaded to it's full pressure potential the .454 Casull can become unreliable and unpleasant to shoot. At upper pressure levels, heavy bullets tend to jump crimp - tying up the cylinder. (wouldn't this be great in an emergency) Also, fired brass can stick in the chambers. 

Buffalo Bore Ammunition feels that a 360 gr. bullet (or 325 gr. bullet at 1525 fps) at 1425 fps is still very powerful, comfortable to shoot, and TOTALLY RELIABLE. At these levels, these bullets give up nothing in killing performance.

title: For Sale:  Acreage For Bug-Out Location, gun ranges and isolation
postcontent: Three lots of raw rural land for sale located 15 miles west of Laramie, Wyoming. Lot prices start at $48,500 for 38 acres and can be very negotiable for the right buyer (neighbor). Overhead or underground electric power is on some lots and can be brought in on lots where it is needed. Land is located on CR 44 (Big Hollow Road), 3 miles N/E of Lake Hattie, 6 miles east from National Forest and just east of Wild Horse Ranch. This land is ideal for those who want to park an RV or build a cabin and enjoy beautiful vistas with very few man made objects within miles. Personally, we are using it for a bug out when the SHTF along with being a nice retreat to target shoot and enjoy the solitude. We would be particularly interested in having like-minded neighbors that would appreciate a place to stock up and feel secure if/when the SHTF. We can build a cabin onsite using classic log building techniques .. our prototype cabin built last summer is shown in the pictures. We also have a sawmill and logs onsite, along with general construction equipment to get your property easily and economically usable for your particular needs. Please note that drilling for water is a hit and miss ordeal in this area, but you can easily haul your own water just like most everybody else living west of Laramie, or have it commercially delivered for $90 per 1500 gallons. The City of Laramie also has two high volume water dispensing depots designed for rural residents. One depot is in Laramie and the other depot is at the water treatment plant which is 10 miles from the property. Bottom line is, hauling water and a cistern holding tank is far more economical and feasible for a getaway cabin. Water well, casing and pump is estimated to be around $20K and that buys a lot of water at $.25/100 gallons at the depots.I am a licensed civil engineer and have lived in Laramie 30 years. I have a local Laramie phone number and address. If interested, shoot me an email and include your phone number so we can talk about being neighbors. All pictures, with the exception of the "big valley" picture, are of the actual property available. The dirt road picture is of the private road that runs through the middle of the development. I look forward to hearing from you!
